Good catch! Rust generics require types to support specific operations. The addition operator `+` isn't defined for all possible types, so the compiler can't guarantee it'll work for arbitrary `T`. To fix this, you'd need to constrain `T` with traits like `Add` or use a macro if more flexibility is needed. Here's an example of adding constraints on type parameters:

```rust
use std::ops::Add;

fn add<T: Add<Output = T>>(a: T, b: T) -> T {
    a + b
}
```
This way, you're saying that `T` must implement the `Add` trait with an output type equal to itself, making sure binary addition is safe.

Sure! Phantom types are a pattern where a type parameter is included purely for compile-time verification, not runtime use. You can encode certain guarantees statically without adding any runtime overhead—say, indicating a value must be positive or never empty. Here’s an example to keep a numeric value always positive:

```rust
type Positive = i32;
struct Number<T>(T);

impl<Positive> Number<Positive> {
    fn new(n: i32) -> Option<Self> {
        if n > 0 { Some(Number(n)) } else { None }
    }
}
```
If you try to create a `Number` with a non-positive integer, the compiler won't compile it. That's powerful for static correctness.

That’s a good start! If you want to enforce rules (say, that `completed` is always either true or false), using enums can add extra safety. Here's an example using sum types with an enum: 

```rust
enum TaskStatus {
    InProgress,
    Completed,
}
struct Task {
    title: String,
    status: TaskStatus,
}
```

Phantom types are useful when you want to encode constraints at compile time but don’t need the value itself. For example, in a library with different backend modules (like SQLite or Postgres), you might use phantom enums to ensure safe conversions without runtime checks: 

```rust
generic struct Database<Backend> {
    // fields here
}
enum Backend { Sqlite, Postgres }
``` 
This enforces type safety at compile time and helps catch bugs.

