```rust
enum Sum<T, U> {
    Left(T),
    Right(U),
}

impl<T, U> Sum<T, U> {
    fn is_left(&self) -> bool {
        matches!(self, Sum::Left(_))
    }
}
```

Makes sense. Here’s the code I tried with unwrap: 

```rust
fn unwrap_left<T, U>(sum: Sum<T, U>) -> T {
    match sum {
        Sum::Left(t) => t,
        Sum::Right(_) => panic!(),
    }
}
```

That’s correct. But be careful with panics! If someone calls this function on a `Sum::Right`, you’ll get a runtime error, which is hard to debug. Instead, returning an `Option` or handling the case explicitly might be better: 

```rust
fn unwrap_left<T, U>(sum: Sum<T, U>) -> Option<T> {
    match sum {
        Sum::Left(t) => Some(t),
        _ => None,
    }
}
```
This way you avoid panics and make your intentions clearer.
